-- Japan, China, South Korea, Thailand: Asian Local Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   F r a n c e s   Y o o n
-- 2010-10-28T21:44:03Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-28/japan-china-south-korea-thailand-asian-local-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  and Finance
Minister Yoshihiko Noda will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The statistics bureau will release at 8:30 a.m. in Tokyo
its reports on September inflation and employment. Consumer
prices excluding fresh food fell 1.0 percent last month from a
year earlier, matching the decrease in August, according to a
Bloomberg News survey. Japan’s unemployment rate was unchanged
from August at 5.1 percent in September, according to a
Bloomberg News survey.  The bureau will publish at 8:30 a.m. its report on overall
household spending for September. Expenditures rose 0.8 percent
in September from a year earlier, after a 1.7 percent increase
in August, another Bloomberg survey showed.  The Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare will publish at
8:30 a.m. in Tokyo its report on the job-to-applicants ratio for
September. Japan’s job-to-applicants ratio rose to 0.55 in
September from 0.54 in August, another Bloomberg survey showed.  The Trade Ministry will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its
preliminary report on industrial production for September.
Japan’s industrial output fell 0.6 percent in September from
August, when it declined 0.5 percent, according to a separate
Bloomberg survey.  The yield on the 0.8 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.905 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 81.01 per dollar at 6:38 a.m. in Sydney.  China: China will sell 28 billion yuan ($4.2 billion) of
three-year bonds.  The yield on the 2.53 percent note due June 2015 was 3.13
percent. The yuan was at 6.6870 per dollar.  South Korea: Manufacturer’s confidence fell to a nine-month
low. An index measuring expectations for November fell to 92
from 99 in October, the Bank of Korea said today.  The statistics office will say industrial production rose
8.7 percent in September from a year earlier, compared with a
17.1 percent gain in August, according to a Bloomberg survey.
The data will be released at 8 a.m. in Seoul.  The yield on the 3.75 note due June 2013 was 3.24 percent,
according to Korea Stock Exchange. The won traded at 1,123.25
per dollar.  Thailand: The Bank of Thailand will release foreign-
exchange reserves data for the week ended Oct. 22. Reserves rose
to $169.1 billion in the previous week.  The central bank will say the country’s current-account
surplus jumped to $2.4 billion in September, from $280 million
in August, according to a Bloomberg survey.  The Ministry of Commerce will report September export
figures. Overseas sales rose 23.6 percent in August from a year
earlier.  The Bank of Thailand will sell 80 billion baht ($2.7
billion) of 14-day bills.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note due March 2021 was 3.16
percent. The baht was at 29.94 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Frances Yoon  in Seoul at 
 fyoon2@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
